ence point developed through extensive collaboration with stakeholders. Since its inception, the value of MISO participation has increased, reaching approximately $5.1 billion in 2024, with cumulative benefitsexceeding $50 billion. MISO membership costs have remained a fraction of the total benefits each year, MISO’s total annual benefits stem from several interconnected factors, each playing a crucial role inenhancing reliability, optimizing market efficiencies and reducing costs. Over time, drivers and the relative contribution of each have evolved.  ...   efficiencies for members and their customers. The following sections provide a detailed breakdown of each component, explaining how MISO’s coordinated approach delivers measurable value to its members andAs a Regional Transmission Operator (RTO), MISO ensures power flows reliably and affordably across its region. The improved reliability metric assesses how MISO’s transmission system performance comparesto non-RTO areas and other RTOs. MISO expects the value derived from improved reliability to keep With the growth of intermittent renewables, rising electrification, emerging technologies and increasingly  ...   In 2024, the annual benefit of improved reliability decreased from the calculated average benefit of $346 million in 2023.  ...   • Load served is collected from EIA 861-M, FERC Electric Assessment Table, MISO Schedule 10, and • MISO uses the TSAI for RTOs in this computation as a conservative measure.• The Cost of Outage is derived from the Lloyds 2015 Business Blackout Study, adjusted annually by the U.S. Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U).  ...   Medium members are assumed to avoid one-third of a large-size member’s avoided FTEs; small members equal one-sixth. • MISO members with multiple operating utilities are assumed to be single members.MISO co-optimizes its energy and ancillary services markets to enhance the efficiency and reliability of grid operations.Ancillary services such as"
